# Workflow Rules

## Worktree Discipline
- At startup, discover and remember the branch or worktree assigned to your role.
- If your assigned worktree is `master`, work in the main project checkout on its current branch; do not expect or create a `.worktrees/<role>` directory for that role.
- Work only in your assigned branch or worktree.
- Do not inspect, diff, merge, or base work on another branch unless that branch is specifically named in a handoff or explicit user instruction.

## Temporary Files
- Use `./tmp/` in your assigned worktree for temporary files; do not use `/tmp`.

## Logbook
- Maintain the tracked root `logbook.jsonl` file for every handoff received or sent.
- Keep `logbook.jsonl` as append-only JSON Lines. Each line is one complete JSON object; never rewrite, reformat, sort, summarize, or merge existing entries.
- Each log entry must include `timestamp`, `direction`, `message`, and `note` fields. Use `direction` values `received`, `sent`, or `queued`.
- When receiving a handoff, append one complete JSON object line to `logbook.jsonl` with a timestamp, direction `received`, the complete handoff message received, and a brief note describing the action taken.
- When sending a handoff, append one complete JSON object line to `logbook.jsonl` with a timestamp, direction `sent`, the complete handoff message sent, and a brief note summarizing the handoff contents.
- If a merge conflict occurs in `logbook.jsonl`, keep all complete JSON lines from both sides. Preserve message text exactly; order chronologically when obvious, otherwise keep both groups intact.
- Commit `logbook.jsonl` updates with the next substantive role-owned commit or outgoing handoff commit. Make a logbook-only commit only when no other work will be committed for that handoff, such as a queued handoff that requires no role-specific work.

## Handoff Format
- For every handoff, write the complete handoff message to `./tmp/<target-role>-handoff.txt`, then send it with `notify-agent.sh <target-role> --file ./tmp/<target-role>-handoff.txt`.
- Start every handoff message with: `Re-read your role and constitution.`
- The specifier invents a short, stable handoff name for each accepted specification handoff.
- Every later handoff for that work must include the specifier handoff name.
- Handoffs must report only essential state, not prescribe process. After the opening line, include exactly these fields and no other prose: sender role, specifier handoff name, branch name, and 10-character commit hash.
- Do not tell the receiving role how to do its job, repeat your process, or ask it to continue sender-owned responsibilities. The normal request is: `Apply your own role rules to this state.`

## Receiving Handoffs
- After receiving a handoff, merge the sender branch state identified by the handoff branch name and 10-character commit hash into your assigned branch before applying your own role rules.
- When receiving a handoff, ignore sender process narrative and decide next actions only from your own role prompt, the constitution, and the current project state.

## Queued Messages
- If one or more messages arrive while you are busy:
  - Save each complete message as its own file in a local untracked `pending-messages/` directory in your assigned worktree.
  - Name queued message files with this format: `PP-YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS-source.txt`, where `PP` is the two-digit priority.
  - Use priority `00` for architect handoffs to coder or refactorer.
  - Use priority `50` for normal messages unless a role prompt or explicit user instruction sets a different priority.
  - Finish the current job before acting on queued messages.
  - After the current job is complete and any required handoff has been sent, process queued message files in sorted filename order.
  - Before removing any queued handoff file, append one complete JSON object line to `logbook.jsonl` with a timestamp, direction `queued`, the complete handoff message from that file, and a note explaining why the queued file is being removed.
  - Delete each queued message file only after processing it. Do not use `rm -f`; use a non-forced deletion command so queue cleanup does not trigger escalation.

## Failure Conditions
- If the expected git layout or assigned worktree is missing, stop and report instead of silently working in the wrong place.
